article.description: The Sun held off a furious late-game rally from the Mystics to win 80-77 on Sunday and clinch their second straight Eastern Conference title.
article.headline: Sun survive Mystics' late rally, win second straight
article.linkText: Sun fend off Mystics for straight Eastern Conference title
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- The champagne was waiting in the
Connecticut locker room and the Washington Mystics made sure the
Sun worked right down to the last second for it.

Nykesha Sales had 17 points and the Sun held off a late-game
rally from the Mystics to win 80-77 and clinch their second
straight Eastern Conference title Sunday.

The former Orlando Miracle, mired for years in mediocrity, moved
to Connecticut three seasons ago and haven't missed the playoffs
since. They came within a game of winning the WNBA championship,
falling to Seattle last season.

The league-leading Sun (23-6) clinched a playoff berth last
week, but winning consecutive conference titles was reason to
celebrate.

"We just had a toast to doing what we did," Sun coach Mike
Thibault said after the post-game bubbly. "When we made the
playoffs, we didn't make a big deal about it, but winning the
Eastern Conference with a couple weeks to go is a great
accomplishment."

It appeared that Connecticut was going to cruise to their second
conference title, up a comfortable 19 points with just over five
minutes to play. The Mystics, it turned out, were just getting
warmed up.

Washington scored 27 points in the final five minutes to roar
back from 19 points down and had a chance to send the game into
overtime with the last possession. But Delisha Milton-Jones
back-rimmed a wide-open 3-pointer as the buzzer sounded and the Sun
survived.

"Sometimes the momentum changes when you are pressing and
hustling around," Mystics coach Richie Adubato said. "We were ice
cold most of the game and then we obviously got on fire right near
the end."

Connecticut extended its winning streak to five and were playing
their second straight game without 7-foot-2 center Margo Dydek, who
is in Poland competing with the Polish national team. And for the
second game, all five starters finished in double-figures. Taj
McWilliams-Franklin, who had 12 points and a team-high seven
rebounds, scored six of the final eight points for Connecticut.

Charlotte Smith-Taylor led the Mystics (14-14) with 17 points
and Alana Beard, who had 11 points in the late-game spurt, finished
with 15.

Lindsay Whalen scored 16 points for Connecticut and Asjha Jones,
starting in place of Dydek, had 11.

"Today was probably good for us so we can see how some of the
(playoff) games might happen," Sales said. "Even though you're up
by 19 points that doesn't mean it's over."

Connecticut led 42-30 at the break and Whalen's layup with 5:13
left in the game gave Connecticut a 69-50 lead. But the Mystics,
battling for the fourth and final playoff spot in the Eastern
Conference, clamped down on defense and began knocking down shots.

"We started pressing fullcourt, which was amazing the way we
got back into the game," Beard said. "Everyone showed a lot of
heart and hustle on the court tonight."

Smith-Taylor grabbed five of her nine rebounds in the run,
converting three into layups. Beard's 3-pointer with 1:01 left
pulled the Mystics to 73-70. Washington was forced to foul the rest
of the way and the Sun hit 5-of-6 from the line.

With 2.4 seconds left, McWilliams-Franklin hit the back end of
her two free throws after missing the first, which would have made
it a two-possession game. The Mystics then ran what coach Richie
Adubato called their "home run play," inbounding to Chasity
Melvin at midcourt, who tossed it backward over her head to
Milton-Jones, waiting and wide-open in the left corner.

But the ball banged off the iron and the Sun celebrated another
Eastern Conference championship.

"I had a good look at the basket, it was just a little too
strong," Milton-Jones said. "It's a designed play and it worked
very well, but the end result wasn't what we expected."
^NOTES: The Sun honored former point guard Debbie Black with at
halftime. The 5-foot-3 Black retired in the offseason after 17
years of professional basketball to become an assistant coach at
Ohio State. The crowd of 7,412 gave Black a standing ovation during
the ceremony.
